## Working style

- Debug like solving a puzzle: hypothesize â†’ test â†’ adapt. Don't guess.
- Sometimes the best fix requires a lot of changes to multiple classes, like changing the type of a field or adding a new class at a higher level.
- If you find yourself writing a function that maps one data structure to another, consider how the objects are used, follow their usages, and refactoring to prevent mapping.
- Prioritize clean and well structured code over easy fixes.
- Don't re-invent the wheel. Use existing libraries and patterns when possible.
- Type safety is paramount. Always use proper types, Pydantic or SqlAlchemy ORM models. Consider our standards as strict as if we were writing in Rust (you will likely port to later).
- Take your time, it's not about writing code fast, it's about writing code elegantly. Write code that Martin Fowler would approve.
- The 'Do one thing' principle means high complexity is almost always worse. Split files, classes, and functions into smaller, more focused units.
- No linting error or warning should be ignored or bypassed. Linting is your ally, not your enemy. A lint error or warning is a real error at runtime. No linting error is difficult to fix if you consult your linting tools and documentation.
- You control the server, ui, and database models. If you need to change a schema or the ui to accommodate new requirements, you are the one who does it. Don't try to adhere to bad patterns just to avoid changing the schema or ui.
- You are still prior to release so you can make big changes without breaking anything. You can write scripts to fix our data and update our schema and ui as needed. You don't need to write code paths that adhere to legacy patterns.
- You got this. Don't just make me proud, make yourself proud. You're the one who will maintain this codebase. You're code quality is an art.

