## Code Rules

### Bad Content Patterns â€” Never Use These

These patterns indicate bad code quality and must never appear in generated code:

**Python:**

- **Never use `Any` or `Unknown` or `object`** â€” use proper types, Pydantic or SqlAlchemy ORM models instead.
- **Never use `dict[str, Any]` or `dict[str, object]` or `dict[Any, Any]` or `dict[Any, object]` or `dict[object, object]` or `dict[Any, str]` or `dict[str, str]`** â€” (you get the picture? these are all hacky ways of avoiding type safety) use typed Pydantic or SqlAlchemy ORM models instead.
- **Never use `# noqa`** â€” fix the lint error instead
- **Never use `# type: ignore`** â€” fix the type error instead

**TypeScript/JavaScript:**

- **Never use `// eslint-disable`** â€” fix the lint error instead
- **Never use `@ts-ignore`** â€” fix the type error instead
- **Never use `@ts-nocheck`** â€” fix the type errors instead
- **Never use `@ts-expect-error`** â€” fix the type error instead

### React and TypeScript Concepts
Key React 19 concepts you must use correctly:

- React Compiler (automatic memoization)
- New `use()` hook for promises/resources
- Server Components (default in App Router)
- Actions (`"use server"`)
- Enhanced `useTransition`, `useDeferredValue`, `useActionState`
- Better error boundaries and Suspense behavior
- No more `defaultProps` or legacy context patterns

When writing React code:

- Prefer Server Components by default
- Use `use()` for async data fetching inside components
- Always use proper TypeScript with `React.FC` only when necessary
- Write clean, modern, idiomatic React 19 code
- Avoid outdated patterns (class components, `componentDidMount`, etc.)

If the user mentions React, assume React 19 + TypeScript + App Router unless told otherwise.

### Code Quality

- `coding-guidelines.md` should be read before writing any code, and any code should follow the guidelines. If you begin to write code without reading the guidelines, you will be wasting time and making mistakes. If you identify that you are not following the guidelines, stop and ask questions or read them back in and work through with your other reference material or online resources.
- Be concise. Show code. Don't describe it.
- Call out problems immediately. If something is fucked, say it's fucked.
- Never leave broken code behind.
- Ask if unclear. Don't guess or shotgun-read files.
- Nothing is 'pre-existing' - the project is always clean with zero lint errors, zero noqa, zero type ignores, and zero failing tests when we start a project. If there are any, that means the previous agent or human made a mistake and we need to clean it up. It doesn't have to be done immediately but no phase of a project should be considered complete until all lint errors and tests are fixed.
- When writing in React, use React 19 syntax. `useEffect` is an old pattern:
  - https://react.dev/blog/2024/12/05/react-19
  - https://react.dev/learn/you-might-not-need-an-effect
